The keys and control panels overlap with the man’s head and shoulders in a collage-like effect. His right hand reaches across the higher keys, while the left hand stays nearer the lower keys and controls. The lighting shifts into cooler blues and bright highlights, giving the instrument and hands a glowing, electronic look. The multiple rows of keys are especially prominent, reinforcing that this is more than a simple single-keyboard organ.\n\nThe image widens again to show the man seated at the organ from the side. He sits on a bench, leaning slightly forward, with both arms extended to the keys. The organ console is to his left, and the rest of the space remains dark. Blue oval patches of light float in the background. His posture stays concentrated and steady, with his attention fixed on the instrument.\n\nThe colors then become highly stylized. The same side view of the player and organ is washed in vivid green, red, yellow, purple, and blue tones, almost like a posterized silhouette. The man’s body, bench, and organ remain recognizable, but the natural colors are replaced by bold psychedelic hues. He continues playing, seated upright but leaning into the keyboard. The background changes from green to yellow, with dark soft-edged shapes drifting around the edges of the image.\n\nNear the end, large centered text appears over the tinted image of the man at the organ. The words read “Orbit III by” in smaller blue lettering above the brand name “WURLITZER” in large red capital letters with a light outline. The player and organ remain blurred and color-shifted behind the text. The background cycles through warm pinks, oranges, and yellows while the logo stays centered and clear, ending with “Orbit III by WURLITZER” as the dominant visual.",
